700800f-a.title: Bronx: Corlear Avenue - 230th Street (West)
700800f-a.text:
Corlear Ave., east side, north from West 230th to 231st Streets,
showing six 2A-story frame dwellings,the last two of which bear Nos.
3022 and 3026 respectively. Also shown are the rears of the St.
John's R.C. Church and the Erotestant Episcopal Church of the Mediator,
both facing on the west side of Kingsbridge Ave.
October 27, 1927.
P. L. Sperr.
NO REPRODUCTIONS.
(2)
The same, at a later date.
May 25, 1937.
P. L. Sperr.
NO REPRODUCTIONS.

700345f-a.title: Bronx: 230th Street (West) - Corlear Avenue
700345f-a.text:
West 230th Street (right, not seen), south side, at the foot of
Corlear Ave. The driveway, here seen, is the vehicular entrance fo
the Kingsbridge freight depot of the New York Central Railroad. It
runs parallel to West 230th Street, the distance of one block from the
foot of Corlear Ave. to the foot of Tibbett Ave. (where automobile
house is located). The freiht house is at this date (1937) being used
bv the Mayone Co. of New York, mason suppliers; a new, large and modern
freight station having been constructed within the freight yards east
of Corlear Ave. The driveway is about 15 feet south of West 230th Street
and is separated by a fence.
October 27, 1927.
P. L. Sperr.
NO REPRODUCTIONS.
